fields.name: name
fields.description:
Name is the name of the lease. Only a single client can hold the lease on
the specified name at any one time.

fields.name: duration
fields.description:
Duration is the duration of the lease. After the duration is reached the
lease can be acquired by other clients.

fields.name: id
fields.description:
Id is the id of the acquired lease. Subsequent calls to release or renew
will need both the lease name and the lease id.

messages.name: Options
messages.description: Options are the options for a type stored in the databroker.

fields.name: capacity
fields.description:
capacity sets a maximum size for the given type. Once the capacity is
reached the oldest records will be removed.
fields.label: optional

fields.name: indexable_fields
fields.description:
indexable_fields sets the protobuf fields that should be indexed on
a record-type's protobuf data whenever records of that type are updated.

!! Only string fields are supported by all backends as a valid indexable target.

Functionality:
 * `user.name` will attempt to index the `name` field on the nested message identified by `user`
 * if invalid fields that do not exist on the message are specified, they are not indexed
 * if a record has an empty value (like "") for the field, it is skipped for indexing.
 * setting this option causes the underlying store to re-index each record
 * for postgres this is a no-op, since the database can index jsonb fields on records
   implicitly

records can then be fetched using a databroker query request using an equals filter
that matches the field-path to the value specified
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: wait
fields.description:
Wait indicates whether to wait for changes or to close the stream on the
last change. The default behavior is to wait for changes.
fields.label: optional

fields.name: server_version
fields.description: the server version indicates the version of the server storing the data

scalarValueTypes.notes: Uses variable-length encoding. Inefficient for encoding negative numbers – if your field is likely to have negative values, use sint32 instead.
Uses variable-length encoding. Inefficient for encoding negative numbers – if your field is likely to have negative values, use sint64 instead.
Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int32s.
Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int64s.
Always four bytes. More efficient than uint32 if values are often greater than 2^28.
Always eight bytes. More efficient than uint64 if values are often greater than 2^56.
A string must always contain UTF-8 encoded or 7-bit ASCII text.
May contain any arbitrary sequence of bytes.
